articles.push({
  slug: "why-your-competitors-will-notice-before-your-customers-do",
  title: "Why Your Competitors Will Notice Before Your Customers Do",
  meta_title: "Why Your Competitors Will Notice Before Your Customers Do",
  excerpt: "The first people who notice your new online presence aren't customers. They're competitors. Customer results take longer -- but they compound.",
  content_type: "deep_dive",
  content_pillar: "growth",
  tags: ["marketing results", "social media ROI", "patience", "compounding"],
  body: 'You have been posting for three weeks. Your Instagram is active. Your Google Business Profile has fresh photos. Blog articles are publishing on your website. Content is going out across Instagram, TikTok, Facebook, YouTube, Pinterest, LinkedIn, X, and Google Business Profile. The engine is running.\n\nBut the phone is not ringing more. Bookings are not up. You are wondering if this is working.\n\nHere is what is actually happening -- and why the first people to notice will not be your customers.\n\n## Your Competitors Notice First\n\nThe first people who see your new presence are the people who watch your market closest: your competitors. The HVAC company owner who searches his own trade in his own city every Monday morning. The salon owner who checks competitor Instagram pages before bed. The restaurant owner who Googles herself weekly and notices who else is showing up.\n\nThey see your Google Business Profile suddenly active with weekly posts and fresh project photos. They see your Instagram going from dormant to consistent. They see a new blog article every week on a website that did not exist two months ago. They see your name appearing in searches where only theirs used to show up.\n\nThis is not vanity. Competitors noticing you is a leading indicator. It means the signals are working. It means you are showing up in the places that matter. It means the visibility engine is doing its job. And it means at least one person in your market is paying attention to what you are doing -- which is more than could be said when your accounts were dark.\n\n## Why Customer Results Take Longer\n\nCustomers do not find you the way competitors do. Competitors are actively watching the market. Customers are living their lives until they have a need. Nobody wakes up on a Tuesday and thinks "I wonder what plumbers have been posting on Instagram lately." They wake up on a Tuesday with a leaking pipe and search "plumber near me."\n\nThe customer journey for a local service business is multi-touch and often invisible. A homeowner sees your post on Facebook in January. They do not need a painter in January. In April, they decide to repaint the exterior. They Google "painters near me." Your name shows up in the Local Pack. Something feels familiar -- they have seen your work before, even if they cannot remember where. They click your listing instead of the other two.\n\nThis is how marketing actually works for local businesses. It is not a direct-response mechanism where a post today generates a call tomorrow. It is a familiarity engine. Every post, every blog article, every GBP photo, every platform presence adds a thin layer of recognition. Those layers accumulate until the moment of need arrives, and when it does, you are the name that feels safe.\n\nThe problem is attribution. The customer who calls will not say "I saw your Instagram post three months ago and it stuck in my head." They will say "I found you on Google." And technically, they did. But Google showed them your listing because your website has fresh content, your GBP is active, and your social signals are strong. The Instagram post they do not remember seeing contributed to the ranking they found you through.\n\n## What Is Actually Happening Behind the Scenes\n\nWhile you are waiting for the phone to ring, several things are compounding that you cannot see.\n\nGoogle is crawling your new content. Every blog article, every GBP post, every website update gets indexed. Google does not rank new content immediately. It watches. It tests. It shows your article for a search query, measures the response, and decides whether to rank it higher or lower. This process takes 4-8 weeks for new content on a new domain. It is not instant, but it is inevitable.\n\nYour social reach is rebuilding. If your accounts were dormant for months, the algorithms demoted you. They stopped showing your content to your followers. Now that you are posting consistently, the algorithms are testing your content with your audience again. Reach recovers gradually, then accelerates. Weeks two through four are the rebuild. Weeks four through eight are when organic reach starts growing beyond your existing followers.\n\nYour Google Business Profile is gaining prominence. Review responses, fresh photos, regular posts, and updated information all feed the prominence signal that determines Local Pack rankings. A GBP listing that has been active for 60 days consistently will outrank one that was active for a week then went silent. Google rewards sustained activity.\n\nYour website authority is building. Every new page -- blog article, portfolio entry, service page -- adds to the keyword footprint of your site. A site with 5 pages can rank for maybe 20 search queries. A site with 25 pages can rank for hundreds. Each page is a fishing line in the water, catching different searches.\n\n## The Compounding Timeline\n\nWeek 1-2: The engine starts. Content publishes. Your accounts come back to life. Competitors notice. Customers do not -- yet.\n\nWeek 3-4: Engagement starts climbing on social platforms. Your existing followers see you again. Some new followers appear. Blog articles are being indexed by Google. Your GBP listing is more active than most competitors.\n\nMonth 2: Search traffic begins. A blog article ranks for a long-tail keyword. A GBP post leads someone to your listing. A Pinterest pin starts getting saved. The first trickle of inbound inquiries that cannot be traced to any single post -- because they came from the cumulative effect of everything.\n\nMonth 3-4: The compound effect is visible. Your website has 15-20 indexed pages. Your social accounts have consistent engagement. Your Google presence is strong enough that you appear in the Local Pack for multiple search terms. The phone starts ringing differently. Not a flood -- a steady increase that grows month over month.\n\nMonth 6+: The flywheel is spinning. Every new project you photograph adds fuel. Your website grows. Your search footprint expands. Your social following compounds. Paid amplification on your best content extends the reach further. The gap between you and competitors who are not doing this widens every month.\n\n## The Hardest Part Is the Gap\n\nThe gap between "the engine is running" and "the results are visible" is the period where most business owners quit. They [quit social media](/blog/how-to-tell-if-your-marketing-is-actually-working) not because it does not work, but because the results are lagged. Effort today, results in 60-90 days. That delay feels like failure when you are in the middle of it.\n\nTraditional advertising does not have this gap. You buy an ad, it runs, you either get calls or you do not. The feedback loop is immediate and clear. But that immediacy is also why it does not compound. When you stop buying ads, the calls stop. There is no residual value.\n\nContent marketing -- social posts, blog articles, website content, GBP activity -- builds an asset. Every post, every article, every photo contributes to a growing body of work that becomes harder for competitors to replicate. An ad gives you today. Content gives you today and every day after.\n\n## The Engine Runs Whether You See Results Yet or Not\n\nThis is the key insight: the engine does not need your belief to work. It needs your photos. As long as you are uploading project series, TracPost is publishing content, writing blog articles, managing your Google Business Profile, hosting your website, and building your search presence across all eight platforms.\n\nThe compounding happens in the background. The algorithms are recalibrating. Google is indexing. Customers are seeing you without knowing they are seeing you. The layers of familiarity are building.\n\nYour competitors noticed in week two. Your customers will notice in month two. The calls will come not because of any single post, but because of the steady accumulation of presence that makes your business feel [like the obvious choice](/blog/why-most-small-businesses-quit-social-media).\n\nThe results are coming. They are just on a longer timeline than an ad, and a much longer timeline than your patience wants them to be. Keep uploading photos. The engine handles the rest.\n\n[TracPost](https://tracpost.com) is the engine. [See how it works](https://tracpost.com).'
});

// ─── Run updates ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

async function main() {
  // Find the TracPost site
  const sites = await sql`
    SELECT s.id FROM sites s
    WHERE s.blog_slug = 'tracpost'
    LIMIT 1
  `;

  if (sites.length === 0) {
    console.error("No site found with blog_slug = 'tracpost'");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const siteId = sites[0].id;
  console.log("Found TracPost site: " + siteId);
  console.log("Total articles to process: " + articles.length + "\n");

  let updated = 0;
  let inserted = 0;
  let errors = 0;

  for (const a of articles) {
    try {
      const existing = await sql`
        SELECT id, status FROM blog_posts WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
      `;

      const schemaJson = {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Article",
        headline: a.title,
        description: a.excerpt,
        author: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
        },
        publisher: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
          logo: {
            "@type": "ImageObject",
            url: "https://tracpost.com/icon.png",
          },
        },
        datePublished: new Date().toISOString(),
        wordCount: a.body.split(/\s+/).length,
        keywords: a.tags.join(", "),
      };

      if (existing.length > 0) {
        // UPDATE -- preserve existing status
        await sql`
          UPDATE blog_posts
          SET
            body = ${a.body},
            title = ${a.title},
            meta_title = ${a.meta_title},
            excerpt = ${a.excerpt},
            meta_description = ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            tags = ${a.tags},
            content_type = ${a.content_type},
            content_pillar = ${a.content_pillar},
            schema_json = ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            updated_at = NOW()
          WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
        `;
        console.log("UPDATED: " + a.slug + " (status preserved: " + existing[0].status + ")");
        updated++;
      } else {
        // INSERT as draft
        await sql`
          INSERT INTO blog_posts (
            site_id, slug, title, body, excerpt,
            meta_title, meta_description, schema_json,
            tags, content_type, content_pillar,
            status, published_at, source
          ) VALUES (
            ${siteId}, ${a.slug}, ${a.title}, ${a.body}, ${a.excerpt},
            ${a.meta_title}, ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            ${a.tags}, ${a.content_type}, ${a.content_pillar},
            'draft', NULL, 'generated'
          )
        `;
        console.log("INSERTED: " + a.slug);
        inserted++;
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("ERROR on " + a.slug + ": " + err.message);
      errors++;
    }
  }

  console.log("\nDone. Updated: " + updated + ", Inserted: " + inserted + ", Errors: " + errors);
}

main().catch(function(err) {
  console.error(err);
  process.exit(1);
});
